Model 1: Monthly Sales vs Marketing Spend

Regression Equation

Monthly Sales=560,777.35+2.1296(Marketing Spend)
Metric	Value
Coefficient	2.1296
R-squared	0.1672
P-value	2.48 × 10⁻¹⁴

Business Interpretation

For every additional ₹1 spent on marketing, monthly sales increase by approximately ₹2.13.
The relationship is statistically significant because the p-value is less than 0.05.
Marketing spend explains 16.7% of the variation in monthly sales.

Is the Variable Useful?

Yes. Marketing spend has a significant positive effect on sales, although it is not a very strong predictor by itself.

Model 2: Monthly Sales vs Footfall

Regression Equation

Monthly Sales=446,410.58+35.6780(Footfall)
Metric	Value
Coefficient	35.6780
R-squared	0.7363
P-value	4.75 × 10⁻⁹⁴

Business Interpretation

Each additional customer visit increases monthly sales by approximately ₹35.68.
The relationship is highly statistically significant.
Footfall explains 73.6% of the variation in monthly sales.

Is the Variable Useful?

Yes. Footfall is a very strong predictor of monthly sales and appears to be one of the most influential variables in the dataset.
